Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)
library(BAS)

Load data

Make sure your data and R Markdown files are in the same directory. When loaded your data file will be called movies. Delete this note when before you submit your work.

load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The data set is comprised of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016.

Since the collection method was a random sample of more than 600 movies (of course way below 10% of the entire population - the number of movies produced in a year is probably higher than 20,000) this allows us to say that the insights we will retrieve from this data are generalizable and non-causual.

Part 2: Data manipulation

movies.red <- movies %>%
          mutate(feature_film = as.factor(ifelse(title_type == 'Feature Film', 'yes', 'no'))) %>%
          mutate(drama = as.factor(ifelse(genre == 'Drama', 'yes', 'no'))) %>%
          mutate(mpaa_rating_R = as.factor(ifelse(mpaa_rating == 'R', 'yes', 'no'))) %>%
          mutate(oscar_season=as.factor(ifelse(thtr_rel_month %in% c(10:12), 'yes', 'no'))) %>%
          mutate(summer_season=as.factor(ifelse(thtr_rel_month %in% c(5:8), 'yes', 'no'))) %>%
          filter(!is.na(runtime)) %>%
          select(feature_film, drama, runtime, mpaa_rating_R, thtr_rel_year, oscar_season, summer_season,
                 imdb_rating, imdb_num_votes, critics_score, audience_score, best_pic_nom, best_pic_win,
                 best_actor_win, best_actress_win, best_dir_win, top200_box)

Part 4: Modeling

Our goal is to predict the popularity of a movie - as quantified by the audience_score variable - using a bayesian regression model with all the predictors contained in the reduced dataset.

bas.lm1 <- bas.lm(audience_score ~ ., data = movies.red, method = 'MCMC',
                 prior = 'ZS-null', modelprior = uniform())

plot(bas.lm1, cex.lab = 0.5)

image(bas.lm1, rotate = FALSE)

The diagnostic charts inform us about the fitness and soundness of the model.

The first diagnostic chart shows the residuals versus the fitted values. These should be randomly scattered around the 0 without showing any clear pattern. Unfortunately this is not the case. There is a wave pattern indicating that the model tended to predict too low for ratings under a value of 30 and over a value of about 75. In between 30 and 75, the model tended to predict high. Above a rating of 75, the residuals appear to scatter randomly.

The second chart shows that the model posterior probability density leveled off at 1 after approximately 3,000 model combinations had been sampled.

The model complexity chart is not very informative in this case, since several model specifications look very similar and their variance is more or less the same (at least from a visual point of view).

The last chart shows the inclusion probabilities of the predictors. The higher the marginal inclusion rate, the more the predictor was used in the models. We can check this also by looking at the last image, that shows exactly this for the top 20 models.

Part 5: Prediction

Lets try to predict the audience_score for the movie Dunkirk (2017). The data were obtained from IMDB, Rotten Tomatoes and Google researches.

Dunkirk <- data.frame(runtime = 106,
                         thtr_rel_year = 2017,
                         imdb_rating = 7.9,
                         imdb_num_votes = 520686,
                         critics_score = 93,
                         audience_score = NA,
                         best_pic_nom = factor("yes", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         best_pic_win = factor("no", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         best_actor_win = factor("no", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         best_actress_win = factor("no", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         best_dir_win = factor("no", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         top200_box = factor("no", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         feature_film = factor("yes", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         drama = factor("yes", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         mpaa_rating_R = factor("no", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         oscar_season = factor("no", levels=c("no", "yes")),
                         summer_season = factor("yes", levels=c("no", "yes")))

BMA_bas.lm1_dunkirk <- predict(bas.lm1, newdata = Dunkirk, estimator = "BMA", se.fit = TRUE)
summary(BMA_bas.lm1_dunkirk)
##             Length Class  Mode     
## fit            1   -none- numeric  
## Ybma           1   -none- numeric  
## Ypred       6386   -none- numeric  
## postprobs   6386   -none- numeric  
## se.fit      6386   -none- numeric  
## se.pred     6386   -none- numeric  
## se.bma.fit     1   -none- numeric  
## se.bma.pred    1   -none- numeric  
## df          6386   -none- numeric  
## best        6386   -none- numeric  
## bestmodel   6386   -none- list     
## best.vars     17   -none- character
## estimator      1   -none- character
BMA_basLM1_predME <- qt(0.95, df = BMA_bas.lm1_dunkirk$se.bma.pred[1]) *
                     mean(BMA_bas.lm1_dunkirk$se.bma.pred)

df <- data.frame("Movie_Title" = "Dunkirk",
                 "Predicted_Rating" = sprintf("%2.1f", BMA_bas.lm1_dunkirk$Ybma),
                 "Prediction_Interval" = sprintf("%2.1f - %2.1f", 
                                                     BMA_bas.lm1_dunkirk$Ybma - BMA_basLM1_predME,
                                                     BMA_bas.lm1_dunkirk$Ybma + BMA_basLM1_predME),
                 "Actual_Rating" = 81)
print(df)
##   Movie_Title Predicted_Rating Prediction_Interval Actual_Rating
## 1     Dunkirk             86.5        68.0 - 105.0            81

Part 6: Conclusion

In this analysis, a parsimonious, linear regression model using bayesian model averaging was created that proved to have some capability for predicting movie popularity based on certain movie characteristics.

Dunkirk movie was predicted to have an 86.5 rating while the actual rating was just 81. This is a very decent result given the scoring scale (0-100).
